### Structs in Go

A struct is a collection of named fields.

### Declaration

```go
type Person struct {
    Name    string
    Age     int
    Email   string
}
```

### Initialization

```go
// Positional (order matters)
p1 := Person{"Alice", 30, "alice@example.com"}

// Named fields (preferred)
p2 := Person{
    Name:  "Bob",
    Age:   25,
    Email: "bob@example.com",
}

// Zero value
var p3 Person
fmt.Println(p3.Name) // ""

// Partial initialization
p4 := Person{Name: "Charlie"}
fmt.Println(p4.Age) // 0
```

### Accessing Fields

```go
p := Person{Name: "Alice", Age: 30}
fmt.Println(p.Name) // Alice
p.Age = 31
fmt.Println(p.Age)  // 31
```

### Structs are Values

```go
a := Person{Name: "Alice"}
b := a                // copy
b.Name = "Bob"
fmt.Println(a.Name)   // Alice (unchanged)
```

### Anonymous Structs

```go
point := struct {
    X, Y int
}{
    X: 10,
    Y: 20,
}
fmt.Println(point.X) // 10
```

### Nested Structs

```go
type Address struct {
    Street string
    City   string
}

type Person struct {
    Name    string
    Address Address
}

p := Person{
    Name: "Alice",
    Address: Address{
        Street: "123 Main St",
        City:   "Springfield",
    },
}
fmt.Println(p.Address.City)
```

### Struct Tags

```go
type User struct {
    ID    int    `json:"id"`
    Name  string `json:"name"`
    Email string `json:"email,omitempty"`
}
```

> **Key Point:** Structs are Go's way of creating complex data types. They are value types (copied on assignment). Use pointers to share struct instances.

codeExample:
package main

import "fmt"

type Car struct {
    Make  string
    Model string
    Year  int
}

func main() {
    // Initialize
    car1 := Car{"Toyota", "Camry", 2022}
    car2 := Car{Make: "Honda", Model: "Civic", Year: 2023}

    fmt.Printf("%+v\n", car1)
    fmt.Printf("%+v\n", car2)

    // Modify
    car1.Year = 2024
    fmt.Println("Updated year:", car1.Year)
}
